{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"100c8285-2707-4850-9776-cce147a0c87f","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the easiest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing Visual Studio or PerfView.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events, GC analysis, or deeper kernel tracing |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (CPU %, GC, thread pool) before committing to a full trace |\n\n### Tip\nIf the service is so loaded it's hard to SSH/RDP in, consider `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first for a lightweight live view, then escalate to `dotnet-trace` once you've confirmed it's worth a full capture.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"57dd036d-6862-4099-884b-6f5e621f6465","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":346},"id":"4f9d4285-6b2d-46fc-a0bb-5eef8913d84b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:35.303Z","parentId":"5b026035-cc34-45d5-b433-f2e5239bb910"}
